{"term":"1957","caseName":"Jones v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/331","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 07, 1958","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13369","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 331, Roy Jones versus United States of America.","start":0,"stop":14.318,"duration":14.32},{"text":"Mr. Asinof.","start":14.318,"stop":16.943,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":16.943,"stop":27.551,"duration":10.61},{"text":"The question involved in this case is on the question of the validity of a search of a private dwelling house and the seizure of contraband articles without a search warrant, the search having been made during the night season and based upon probable cause in a case wherein the federal agents had ample opportunity to procure a valid search warrant.","start":27.551,"stop":67.498,"duration":39.95},{"text":"The case arose in the District Court for the Northern District of Georgia and from the facts found by the trial judge after hearing a motion to suppress the evidence in the case of certain articles that were found inside the house.","start":67.498,"stop":89.767,"duration":22.27},{"text":"The trial judge found that there was ample opportunity to procure a search warrant, there being five officers in approximately two doors.","start":89.767,"stop":101.53,"duration":11.76},{"text":"The evidence disclosed before the trial judge that the agents of the Government had had the dwelling house under observation for approximately three days, that they had probable cause for believing that a -- an illicit distillery was in operation inside the house.","start":101.53,"stop":124.037,"duration":22.51},{"text":"Without going into the question of the facts that gave them -- that gave rise to the probable cause, we will concede and it concede in the trial court and in the Court of Appeals that there was probable cause.","start":124.037,"stop":136.822,"duration":12.78},{"text":"On the afternoon of --","start":136.822,"stop":138.02,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Probable cause for -- for what?","start":138.02,"stop":140.074,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"For the procuring of a warrant.","start":140.074,"stop":141.339,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"For -- to have gotten a warrant.","start":141.339,"stop":142.236,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes, sir.","start":142.236,"stop":144.901,"duration":2.67},{"text":"During the afternoon that the --","start":144.901,"stop":146.636,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and I think the detail and fact are essential, it seems to me, in this time of the case.","start":146.636,"stop":153.708,"duration":7.07},{"text":"Is the -- the probable cause derived on your concession and your present statement on the basis of what they'd observed over what period of time?","start":153.708,"stop":163.335,"duration":9.63}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Over a period of three days.","start":163.335,"stop":164.543,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when did -- when did the situation develop that lead you to say at that point they could have got a search warrant?","start":164.543,"stop":174.782,"duration":10.24},{"text":"When was it?","start":174.782,"stop":175.978,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":175.978,"stop":176.116,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you say the second day or third day?","start":176.116,"stop":177.322,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"I would have to answer it in this way, if Your Honor please.","start":177.322,"stop":181.915,"duration":4.59},{"text":"On the afternoon of the -- on the afternoon when the actual search was made --","start":181.915,"stop":186.689,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- but out of (Voice Overlap) --","start":186.689,"stop":187.348,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the search was made at 9:15 but during the afternoon about 1 o' clock --","start":187.348,"stop":190.192,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) at night?","start":190.192,"stop":191.358,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":191.358,"stop":192.773,"duration":1.41},{"text":"About 1 o'clock in the afternoon, the agents went to Gainesville, some distance of just a few miles, and procured a daytime search warrant, a daylight search warrant based on the information or the probable cause that they had.","start":192.773,"stop":207.603,"duration":14.83},{"text":"The Commission had issued a warrant to the agents to execute a search warrant during the daylight hours.","start":207.603,"stop":215.286,"duration":7.68},{"text":"They then --","start":215.286,"stop":215.494,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that customary to have the search warrant state when it made the (Voice Overlap) --","start":215.494,"stop":219.933,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, Rule 41 (c) provides that if the -- if the affidavits are positive that -- that the contraband is in the house, then the Commission may -- may authorize the search to be made at any time --","start":219.933,"stop":231.644,"duration":11.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You --","start":231.644,"stop":232.44,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but if they are based upon information and belief, then he may only direct the search to be made in the daytime.","start":232.44,"stop":239.027,"duration":6.59},{"text":"That is one of the points that -- that I will develop in my argument.","start":239.027,"stop":241.799,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that was (Inaudible)","start":241.799,"stop":244.474,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":244.474,"stop":244.913,"duration":0.44},{"text":"That is the search warrant that they had but the Government does not and never has contended it was used.","start":244.913,"stop":250.451,"duration":5.54},{"text":"Now, what they did?","start":250.451,"stop":251.2,"duration":0.75},{"text":"They waited until 9:15 that night until after it became dark.","start":251.2,"stop":256.007,"duration":4.81},{"text":"The trial judge found that the reason that they had waited was because the agents wanted to see if they could see some other vehicles that they might have seen going in or coming out of that property.","start":256.007,"stop":269.745,"duration":13.74},{"text":"So, at 9:15 at night, they made their initial move to search the premises.","start":269.745,"stop":276.292,"duration":6.55},{"text":"At the time the petitioner, Roy Jones, was not at home but his wife and little boy had come in the front door and had blocked the entrance to the door and asked him not to come in, to wait until the husband came home, not with --","start":276.292,"stop":293.133,"duration":16.84}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, right there, did -- what did the officers tell the wife?","start":293.133,"stop":297.003,"duration":3.87},{"text":"What's the reason they wanted to go in?","start":297.003,"stop":298.8,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"To search.","start":298.8,"stop":300.335,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the only reason they go --","start":300.335,"stop":301.95,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the reason that the -- that the agents gave according to the record is that they didn't need -- she asked them for a warrant.","start":301.95,"stop":309.177,"duration":7.23},{"text":"She said, “Where is your warrant?”","start":309.177,"stop":311.103,"duration":1.93},{"text":"They said, “We don't need a warrant, we're coming in.”","start":311.103,"stop":313.788,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"For what purpose did they --","start":313.788,"stop":314.856,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they did not, at that time, state what they were going in there for.","start":314.856,"stop":318.447,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did they, at any time before they went by her and into the house, say why it was they wanted to go in?","start":318.447,"stop":324.563,"duration":6.12}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"They just said -- according to the record they said, “We are federal law.","start":324.563,"stop":329.172,"duration":4.61},{"text":"We are coming in, we do not need a warrant.”","start":329.172,"stop":331.196,"duration":2.02},{"text":"That is what the records show.","start":331.196,"stop":332.122,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there any fact finding whether with there was any stated purpose and what's that stated purpose was?","start":332.122,"stop":336.563,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe that the trial judge found.","start":336.563,"stop":339.016,"duration":2.45},{"text":"He did find that -- that -- I believe that the findings of fact made by the trial judge are quite extensive, quite lengthy.","start":339.016,"stop":345.117,"duration":6.1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did he make any finding on this specific --","start":345.117,"stop":348.279,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":348.279,"stop":348.596,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- matter or purpose?","start":348.596,"stop":348.856,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"He -- he made the finding of fact in there that the reason that they did not execute the warrant in the daytime was because they wanted to see if they could find some vehicles --","start":348.856,"stop":359.555,"duration":10.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's what I -- that's what I'm talking about.","start":359.555,"stop":361.461,"duration":1.91},{"text":"What did they tell the wife before they went in?","start":361.461,"stop":364.136,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"They told her, “We are going in.”","start":364.136,"stop":367.523,"duration":3.39},{"text":"They did not state that -- they just simply, according to the record, said to her, “We are federal law.","start":367.523,"stop":374.507,"duration":6.98},{"text":"We do not need a warrant.","start":374.507,"stop":375.653,"duration":1.15},{"text":"We're coming in.”","start":375.653,"stop":376.29,"duration":0.64},{"text":"I don't think that there was any specific language used by them to say, “We're going in for either to --","start":376.29,"stop":380.909,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now did the trial judge make any finding whether there was any specific language used by them as to purpose?","start":380.909,"stop":388.05,"duration":7.14}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":388.05,"stop":389.216,"duration":1.17},{"text":"I don't recall any specific language that was used along.","start":389.216,"stop":392.168,"duration":2.95},{"text":"But that is to say as to the purpose they went.","start":392.168,"stop":394.264,"duration":2.1},{"text":"However, they agent who was in charged did testify and he was asked two or three times, and I pointed it out in my reply brief, that he was asked several times why they -- why they went in there, and his reply to it was, to the effect that they had gone in for that purpose.","start":394.264,"stop":413.145,"duration":18.88},{"text":"He just -- he never did say that they had gone in to arrest anyone or place anyone under arrest.","start":413.145,"stop":417.556,"duration":4.41},{"text":"That was the Government contends in this case that the -- that the purpose of going in the house was that the officers had probable cause to believe that a felony was being committed inside the house and having that probable cause that they had the right to go in to make an arrest without a warrant.","start":417.556,"stop":432.516,"duration":14.96},{"text":"And that after they got in the house that they discovered that there was an illicit distillery in the house, and being in there lawfully, they had the right to see the illicit distillery.","start":432.516,"stop":441.816,"duration":9.3},{"text":"That was the point that's made by the Government.","start":441.816,"stop":443.773,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, is there any evidence that the wife told the officers before they went to inquire and into the house that the husband was not at home?","start":443.773,"stop":451.775,"duration":8}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, yes, sir, she specifically says, “My husband is not at home.","start":451.775,"stop":455.785,"duration":4.01},{"text":"Wait until Roy comes back.”","start":455.785,"stop":457.749,"duration":1.96},{"text":"And they -- they went in.","start":457.749,"stop":459.835,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there any finding whether or not the husband was in the house?","start":459.835,"stop":463.017,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"The finding is to the effect that the husband was not in the house and came there by an hour later.","start":463.017,"stop":467.496,"duration":4.48},{"text":"He was placed under arrest after the distillery had been seized.","start":467.496,"stop":471.587,"duration":4.09},{"text":"Now, getting to the point that they had secured a daylight search warrant, they went in the premises at 9:15 at night and the trial judge found, as a matter of fact, that the reason that they had waited was an order that they could find vehicles either going in or coming out.","start":471.587,"stop":492.341,"duration":20.75},{"text":"But they -- the probable cause that we contend that they had and the record shows that they had, exist at the time they went to Gainesville to procure the daylight search warrant and based on that, the magistrate authorized him to make a daylight search.","start":492.341,"stop":505.983,"duration":13.64},{"text":"He did not make a daylight search and the trial judge found, and it was conceded by the Government in the trial court in the record, that the search was not made pursuant to the daylight search warrant but was made based on probable cause.","start":505.983,"stop":520.248,"duration":14.27},{"text":"Now, the actual finding made by the trial judge, that is to say the conclusions of law that the Court reached in -- in overruling the motion to suppress was based solely upon the Rabinowitz case.","start":520.248,"stop":536.902,"duration":16.65},{"text":"It was decided by this Court some few years ago on the theory as the trial judge held and upheld in a per curiam decision by the Court of Appeals that if the officers have probable cause that they do not need a search warrant.","start":536.902,"stop":556.818,"duration":19.92},{"text":"We contend that probable cause, as used in the Constitution in the Fourth Amendment, relates to what is necessary in order to procure a search warrant and not what must exist in order for the officer to make a search.","start":556.818,"stop":573.045,"duration":16.23},{"text":"The language used in the Fourth Amendment would require such a construction","start":573.045,"stop":576.718,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean -- you think that the Court read the Rabinowitz case as saying independently of an arrest that if you have probable cause, you can search without a warrant?","start":576.718,"stop":588.761,"duration":12.04}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":588.761,"stop":589.368,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the way they read it?","start":589.368,"stop":590.614,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the -- that is the construction or the interpretation that I believe that you would have to put on the trial judge's opinion in this case.","start":590.614,"stop":598.866,"duration":8.25},{"text":"The trial judge --","start":598.866,"stop":599.106,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But that's not the view of the Government here, as I understand.","start":599.106,"stop":601.998,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the -- the Government takes a new view after --","start":601.998,"stop":604.391,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government takes the view that there has to have been probable cause for an arrest and the search incident to that arrest.","start":604.391,"stop":611.074,"duration":6.68}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the Government now takes this view.","start":611.074,"stop":613.479,"duration":2.41},{"text":"The Government now in this Court, for the first time, takes the view that -- that in this case that the officers or the agents had probable cause to make an arrest and that they have a right to go into a house to make an arrest without a warrant and that after they got in there, they incidentally found that there was an illicit distillery in the house.","start":613.479,"stop":634.366,"duration":20.89}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So they're not defending the view of the trial judge.","start":634.366,"stop":638.685,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the language that's used in the brief, I -- it -- it's not fully clear to me as to exactly which view they are taking.","start":638.685,"stop":646.231,"duration":7.55},{"text":"They say that they do not read the opinion of the trial judge upon which the Court of Appeals affirmed as justifying the conclusion that the raid was made or the seizure was made for the purpose of going in there without going in to make an arrest.","start":646.231,"stop":663.296,"duration":17.07},{"text":"But the way I read it, of course, it -- it seems to me clear, one way or the other that they did go in and that they had a probable cause and they had submission time to procure one.","start":663.296,"stop":672.723,"duration":9.43},{"text":"I raised this pointed, if -- if the Court please, that when the officers or the agents went to Gainesville to procure the daylight search warrant, that they had the probable cause at that time, whether they were going in for the purpose of -- of seizing the distillery or arresting the petitioner because of the probable cause that they had to arrest him, they could have, at that time, have procured a warrant to arrest him if that probable cause exists at that time and the Government contends that it did.","start":672.723,"stop":702.448,"duration":29.73},{"text":"But they did not, at any time, attempt to procure a warrant to arrest or to search with the exception of the daylight search warrant that they did actually procure.","start":702.448,"stop":711.888,"duration":9.44},{"text":"Now, the trial judge in his -- in his findings of fact -- now, we -- there's no question but what there were a sufficient number of officers.","start":711.888,"stop":728.443,"duration":16.55},{"text":"And the trial judge said that although the officers had ample opportunity to execute the daylight search warrant during the daylight hours, they did not do so but desiring to see as any vehicles engaged in removing the illicit liquors, they did not immediately execute the daylight search warrant but remained on watching until after dark until about 9 o'clock p.m.","start":728.443,"stop":752.579,"duration":24.14},{"text":"And this, I believe, would answer Your Honor's question that at that time, the officers attempt to gain entrance in the dwelling of Roy Jones who was not at home at that time.","start":752.579,"stop":761.464,"duration":8.89},{"text":"Mrs.Jones attempted to block the doorway requesting the officers to wait until the husband arrives.","start":761.464,"stop":766.94,"duration":5.48},{"text":"And at that time, a 12-year old son of the appellant obtained a shotgun and held it in a threatening manner in an attempt to keep the officers from searching the premises.","start":766.94,"stop":775.794,"duration":8.85},{"text":"Mrs. Jones asked the officer if he had a search warrant, and he stated that he did not need one.","start":775.794,"stop":780.772,"duration":4.98},{"text":"In other words, she specifically did ask, according to the record, for a search warrant.","start":780.772,"stop":785.241,"duration":4.47},{"text":"So we contend that if the officers had gone in there for any purpose other than the search of the premises, they would have, at that time, stated so.","start":785.241,"stop":792.864,"duration":7.62},{"text":"But they went in regardless without a search warrant.","start":792.864,"stop":795.14,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, did I understand you?","start":795.14,"stop":796.705,"duration":1.57},{"text":"There was no warrant of arrest here, was there?","start":796.705,"stop":798.629,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"There was no warrant whatsoever.","start":798.629,"stop":799.787,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that I don't understand if I did understand you correctly, the Government's defense here is that if you have a warrant of arrest, incidentally, you may search.","start":799.787,"stop":809.636,"duration":9.85},{"text":"That is -- the case doesn't present that.","start":809.636,"stop":811.932,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, they contend this.","start":811.932,"stop":815.924,"duration":3.99},{"text":"The Rabinowitz case is a case wherein the -- the deputy marshals having a valid warrant of arrest went in to arrest the petitioner and at that time, incidental to the service --","start":815.924,"stop":830.332,"duration":14.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand but how does that help this case?","start":830.332,"stop":832.957,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"They contend -- they -- they're asking for an extension of that case into --into this sort of a situation that where officers have probable cause to -- to make an arrest without a warrant.","start":832.957,"stop":846.01,"duration":13.05},{"text":"They contend that they have the right to go in to private property in order to make that arrest and then after they're in there, incidentally, if they find illicit property that they therefore have the right to seize.","start":846.01,"stop":856.146,"duration":10.14},{"text":"We contend that's not the law.","start":856.146,"stop":857.344,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'll wait until they say but what you're -- what -- I asked this question because I know what you arguable -- I'd like to know what your argument is.","start":857.344,"stop":864.697,"duration":7.35},{"text":"As I understand you, you say the Rabinowitz case says, having a warrant of arrest, you may incidentally search.","start":864.697,"stop":872.519,"duration":7.82},{"text":"Here, you have no warrant of arrest, though the premise of the Rabinowitz case is out but because if you have a warrant, you may search without a search warrant.","start":872.519,"stop":883.076,"duration":10.56},{"text":"In this case, you could have arrested without a warrant of arrest therefore, you can also search.","start":883.076,"stop":887.525,"duration":4.45},{"text":"I don't understand that.","start":887.525,"stop":888.194,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't understand that either, Your Honor.","start":888.194,"stop":889.809,"duration":1.62},{"text":"That -- that is the very point that -- that's the very point that I'm -- I'm merely trying to argue against the Government's contention.","start":889.809,"stop":895.366,"duration":5.56},{"text":"I do not understand --","start":895.366,"stop":897.001,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you said something else that -- I followed but I wondered if you -- you're free to argue, mainly, that the unreasonable of the Fourth Amendment relates not unreasonable in abstract or that is if it, from the point of view of the world outside, bear unreasonable or reasonable.","start":897.001,"stop":918.636,"duration":21.63},{"text":"You say the unreasonableness is related to what it is you're getting search warrant for.","start":918.636,"stop":922.661,"duration":4.02},{"text":"Is that what you've said?","start":922.661,"stop":923.517,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"I say if -- if Your Honor please that -- that where a sufficient time exists to procure a search warrant and the officers do not procure one and there is no emergency or unusual circumstances or it is not incidental to a lawful arrest upon a valid warrant of arrest, that they do not have the right to make the search without a valid search warrant.","start":923.517,"stop":946.298,"duration":22.78},{"text":"But in such cases, they must procure a valid search warrant where it is practicable to procure one.","start":946.298,"stop":952.262,"duration":5.96},{"text":"In other words, the Rabinowitz --","start":952.262,"stop":954.228,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I understood you to say that.","start":954.228,"stop":956.713,"duration":2.49},{"text":"But is that what the case has thus far allow you to say?","start":956.713,"stop":961.234,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- that is my interpretation that this Court placed upon a case --","start":961.234,"stop":964.607,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You say -- are you -- are you saying that the cases do not justify Government's accuse to stand on the case that you're arguing?","start":964.607,"stop":975.242,"duration":10.63},{"text":"You may consider whether or not it was unreasonable or reasonable not with the presupposition with the starting point that if you can, you must get a search warrant, but in the context of what took place, forget all about the Fourth Amendment, or this a reasonable or unreasonable search.","start":975.242,"stop":993.745,"duration":18.5}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"It was an unreasonable search.","start":993.745,"stop":995.38,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I'm saying, isn't -- isn't that what the case is?","start":995.38,"stop":998.651,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":998.651,"stop":998.978,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's the talk of the cases and this Court upheld --","start":998.978,"stop":1001.284,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1001.284,"stop":1001.931,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- namely, if you don't start out at the necessity of getting your search warrant, if it's feasible to do so, what you'd consider independently of all that was this a reasonable or an unreasonable search in relation to what they did.","start":1001.931,"stop":1016.978,"duration":15.05}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1016.978,"stop":1017.946,"duration":0.97},{"text":"I think it was in view of the -- in view --","start":1017.946,"stop":1019.675,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but I'm suggesting to you if the case is, if I understand it, allow the Government to say you don't start out with the duty to get a search warrant if you can.","start":1019.675,"stop":1031.251,"duration":11.58}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not understand that the -- that the law authorizes the Government to make a search of a private dwelling house except in two instances.","start":1031.251,"stop":1039.097,"duration":7.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the Taylor case flatly against that?","start":1039.097,"stop":1041.919,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, Your Honor, the Taylor case is not against that.","start":1041.919,"stop":1044.285,"duration":2.37},{"text":"In the Taylor case, as I -- as I recall, the Government relies upon the Taylor case but we do also -- the Taylor case did not hold that Your Honor.","start":1044.285,"stop":1055.447,"duration":11.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What about the Rabinowitz?","start":1055.447,"stop":1057.142,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"The Rabinowitz case is --","start":1057.142,"stop":1058.427,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Rabinowitz made it reasonable because you had a warrant of arrest.","start":1058.427,"stop":1061.681,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1061.681,"stop":1062.268,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But that has nothing to do with getting the right to search.","start":1062.268,"stop":1065.36,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- that, of course, is -- that, of course, is what made it reasonable in the Rabinowitz case.","start":1065.36,"stop":1069.849,"duration":4.49},{"text":"It made --","start":1069.849,"stop":1069.869,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So therefore -- therefore it negative the requirements that you urge, namely, you have to consider whether they can get a search warrant.","start":1069.869,"stop":1078.658,"duration":8.79}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1078.658,"stop":1079.494,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And if they can, then they can't search without it.","start":1079.494,"stop":1081.86,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1081.86,"stop":1082.567,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, how does the fact that you can arrest, give them leave to disregard the requirement of getting a search warrant?","start":1082.567,"stop":1087.375,"duration":4.81}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not believe it does.","start":1087.375,"stop":1088.932,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But doesn't the case hold that?","start":1088.932,"stop":1091.128,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know what case, Your Honor.","start":1091.128,"stop":1092.516,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Rabinowitz.","start":1092.516,"stop":1093.602,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"The Rabinowitz case does not hold that, Your Honor.","start":1093.602,"stop":1095.516,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What does it hold?","start":1095.516,"stop":1096.484,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"It holds -- it holds incidental to a -- to a valid warrant of arrest that --","start":1096.484,"stop":1101.911,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we're seeing the same thing.","start":1101.911,"stop":1103.967,"duration":2.06},{"text":"What do you mean by incidental?","start":1103.967,"stop":1105.354,"duration":1.39},{"text":"It means if you can arrest, you don't have to get a search warrant.","start":1105.354,"stop":1109.257,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1109.257,"stop":1109.574,"duration":0.32},{"text":"If -- well, that -- in that case, though it was a -- it was an arrest was made upon a valid warrant of arrest.","start":1109.574,"stop":1116.97,"duration":7.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes, but it means that if you can make a valid arrest, you don't have to bother about a search warrant.","start":1116.97,"stop":1122.946,"duration":5.98},{"text":"Is that right?","start":1122.946,"stop":1124.503,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1124.503,"stop":1125.319,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Therefore, the requirement of getting a search warrant if you can is not the doctrine of this Court according to the cases today.","start":1125.319,"stop":1133.329,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now according --","start":1133.329,"stop":1134.188,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what did the search bring?","start":1134.188,"stop":1136.481,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Provided the search is reasonable.","start":1136.481,"stop":1138.108,"duration":1.63},{"text":"Now --","start":1138.108,"stop":1138.268,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) nothing.","start":1138.268,"stop":1138.933,"duration":0.66},{"text":"But bearing on the unreasonableness, the fact that you get a search warrant isn't relevant, is that right?","start":1138.933,"stop":1145.131,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1145.131,"stop":1145.838,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1145.838,"stop":1145.996,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could --","start":1145.996,"stop":1146.34,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Reasonableness is the main -- is the main (Voice Overlap) --","start":1146.34,"stop":1148.474,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Reasonableness unrelated to your opportunity or rather the opportunity of the law which is to get a search warrant.","start":1148.474,"stop":1155.608,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"But, of course, reasonable -- that would be one of the elements of reasonableness, that is to say whether or not --","start":1155.608,"stop":1160.496,"duration":4.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not according to the cases.","start":1160.496,"stop":1162.672,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that --","start":1162.672,"stop":1163.249,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But what's the element of (Inaudible)","start":1163.249,"stop":1166.64,"duration":3.39}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"But then, the Jeffers case, if -- if Your Honor please, that Jeffers case change that.","start":1166.64,"stop":1171.211,"duration":4.57},{"text":"Now, in the Jeffers case, this Court went on and said over and again, this Court has emphasized that the mandate of the amendment requires adherence to judicial processes.","start":1171.211,"stop":1184.245,"duration":13.03},{"text":"Only where incidental to a valid arrest or in exceptional circumstances may an exemption lie and then the burden is on those seeking the exemption to show the need for.","start":1184.245,"stop":1194.981,"duration":10.74},{"text":"Now, that, of course, is -- was the one of the latest expressions by this Court and was an expression related in the Rabinowitz case.","start":1194.981,"stop":1203.312,"duration":8.33},{"text":"Now, the trial judge found in this case, as a matter of fact, that if the officers have probable cause to procure -- to -- to make the search that they do not need a search warrant, now, if that is the law, then all need for search warrants is at an end because, as I understand, the decisions thus far that in order to procure a valid search warrant, the officers must first have a probable cause.","start":1203.312,"stop":1231.671,"duration":28.36},{"text":"And probable cause is something that must be determined by a -- an impartial magistrate and not by the officers themselves.","start":1231.671,"stop":1239.676,"duration":8},{"text":"In order to procure a valid warrant to search, the magistrate must pass upon whether or not those circumstances are sufficient to show it.","start":1239.676,"stop":1248.707,"duration":9.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, wasn't all has been -- what you've just said, all been set (Inaudible) as well in a number of dissenting opinions and are you asking the Court to overrule the cases in which those are dissenting views --","start":1248.707,"stop":1259.503,"duration":10.8}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no.","start":1259.503,"stop":1259.681,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- rather than court views?","start":1259.681,"stop":1260.986,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":1260.986,"stop":1261.376,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't think we have to overrule anything besides --","start":1261.376,"stop":1263.17,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I do not.","start":1263.17,"stop":1264.478,"duration":1.31},{"text":"I do not except --","start":1264.478,"stop":1264.755,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1264.755,"stop":1265.444,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"-- except the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals in this case.","start":1265.444,"stop":1269.336,"duration":3.89},{"text":"I don't --","start":1269.336,"stop":1269.646,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They're not for your purposes but is it --","start":1269.646,"stop":1271.231,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1271.231,"stop":1271.379,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- according to the due regard for what has been said here before?","start":1271.379,"stop":1277.046,"duration":5.67},{"text":"Isn't it enough to say the Court of Appeals is wrong, if they acted on what the Court has decided?","start":1277.046,"stop":1281.106,"duration":4.06}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they did not act on what this Court has decided, if Your Honor please, because the Court of Appeals has just wrote a per curiam decision in this case affirming the trial judge.","start":1281.106,"stop":1288.699,"duration":7.59},{"text":"And the trial judge based it upon the Rabinowitz case which is not in point.","start":1288.699,"stop":1293.996,"duration":5.3},{"text":"It is not in point with the facts of this case.","start":1293.996,"stop":1296.985,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Would the arrest here (Inaudible)","start":1296.985,"stop":1301.197,"duration":4.21}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- no, Your Honor.","start":1301.197,"stop":1302.912,"duration":1.72},{"text":"There -- there was no arrest made in the house and that is the point in this case.","start":1302.912,"stop":1307.401,"duration":4.49},{"text":"The Government contends --","start":1307.401,"stop":1308.389,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1308.389,"stop":1310.595,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"They did not.","start":1310.595,"stop":1311.501,"duration":0.91},{"text":"That was a 12-year old boy.","start":1311.501,"stop":1313.218,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"He is inside the house?","start":1313.218,"stop":1314.244,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, he was inside the house.","start":1314.244,"stop":1316.048,"duration":1.8},{"text":"But there was no arrest made in the house.","start":1316.048,"stop":1319.511,"duration":3.46},{"text":"The Government contends that the officers now, the Government contends that the -- that the agents went in for the purpose of making an arrest, although there's no evidence in the record to indicate that.","start":1319.511,"stop":1329.628,"duration":10.12}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, isn't the Government's position that they might reasonably believe that the husband was in the house in spite the wife's denial of it and having reasonable or probable cause to believe that he's guilty of the crime may enter to the house for the purpose of arresting him even though he wasn't there, that their entry for that purpose justified their seizing the evidence which was subsequently used against them to convict him?","start":1329.628,"stop":1356.031,"duration":26.4}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the Government's contention but there is no evidence in the record, no statement by any agent that he went in there for that purpose.","start":1356.031,"stop":1363.047,"duration":7.02},{"text":"There's no -- there's no statement they have been watching the house for about three days.","start":1363.047,"stop":1366.844,"duration":3.8},{"text":"During that time, there's no evidence that they saw the petitioner going in or coming out.","start":1366.844,"stop":1370.984,"duration":4.14},{"text":"There's no evidence that they thought or believed he was in there.","start":1370.984,"stop":1374.186,"duration":3.2},{"text":"There's no evidence that he had -- that they had anytime attempted to procure a warrant to arrest him or not.","start":1374.186,"stop":1379.583,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, are you telling us that this is the first time the Government has sought to sustain --","start":1379.583,"stop":1382.817,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1382.817,"stop":1384.072,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- this seizure on the basis of an entry with probable --","start":1384.072,"stop":1387.516,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1387.516,"stop":1387.853,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- cause to believe that the husband was there and --","start":1387.853,"stop":1390.209,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct --","start":1390.209,"stop":1390.457,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1390.457,"stop":1391.074,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that is not position taken by the Government in -- in the trial Court and it was not the position taken by the Government in the appellate -- in the Court of Appeals but the position was first taken in this Court.","start":1391.074,"stop":1401.588,"duration":10.51},{"text":"Now, we have, in this case -- we -- we contend this, that there is a distinction between a daylight search warrant and a nighttime search warrant, a distinction made by Rule 41 (c).","start":1401.588,"stop":1414.831,"duration":13.24},{"text":"And I noticed that the Government in their responds, in their response brief, has not, at any time, sought to answer that argument.","start":1414.831,"stop":1422.623,"duration":7.79},{"text":"And the argument is this, that it requires positive affidavits in order to procure a nighttime search warrant and merely probable affidavit stating probable cause to procure a daylight search warrant.","start":1422.623,"stop":1439.021,"duration":16.4},{"text":"The officers in this case did not at the time they went in to make the search whether with or without the warrant at 9:15 at night.","start":1439.021,"stop":1445.775,"duration":6.75},{"text":"They did not have positive information that a distillery was in operation in the house, and they went in.","start":1445.775,"stop":1451.533,"duration":5.76},{"text":"And we contend that even under Rule 41 (c), that even a magistrate, even the entire judicial power of the -- of the United States could not, under those facts, have authorized a search during the night season.","start":1451.533,"stop":1465.392,"duration":13.86},{"text":"And that when the officers did in this case when they -- when they went in and -- and made the seizure, during the night season, that they went further that then -- then the entire judicial power of the United States could have actually authorized under Rule 41 (c).","start":1465.392,"stop":1481.347,"duration":15.95},{"text":"Now, this is a point that I have raised in my brief and the Government has not answered.","start":1481.347,"stop":1485.676,"duration":4.33}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You have better points on the matter.","start":1485.676,"stop":1487.283,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I have better ones than that and -- if Your Honor please.","start":1487.283,"stop":1491.035,"duration":3.75},{"text":"But we -- we contend that in this case that the Government -- the Government's main point that they raise is, that they went in to make an arrest, that that was the purpose of going in.","start":1491.035,"stop":1501.334,"duration":10.3},{"text":"We say that there is absolutely not want to order of testimony in the record.","start":1501.334,"stop":1506.542,"duration":5.21},{"text":"There's no evidence and there's no fact finding or -- or finding of fact by the trial judge to sustain the contention made by the Government to this effect.","start":1506.542,"stop":1515.449,"duration":8.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it make -- does it make any difference this was contraband?","start":1515.449,"stop":1519.559,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think it made no difference, Your Honor, because of the fact that the Constitution still stands between the -- the Government and the citizen to protect them for many unreasonable search and seizure.","start":1519.559,"stop":1532.401,"duration":12.84},{"text":"And this was an unreasonable search and seizure according to the record in this case.","start":1532.401,"stop":1535.812,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what was seized?","start":1535.812,"stop":1537.279,"duration":1.47},{"text":"A steel?","start":1537.279,"stop":1537.688,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"It was a steel.","start":1537.688,"stop":1538.856,"duration":1.17},{"text":"A steel -- a contraband steel was seized.","start":1538.856,"stop":1541.466,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What steel?","start":1541.466,"stop":1542.242,"duration":0.78},{"text":"Big one?","start":1542.242,"stop":1542.981,"duration":0.74},{"text":"Small one?","start":1542.981,"stop":1543.548,"duration":0.57},{"text":"What?","start":1543.548,"stop":1543.835,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"It was -- it was what was known as a large-type steel.","start":1543.835,"stop":1546.879,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Difficult to move or (Inaudible)","start":1546.879,"stop":1548.666,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they destroyed it according to the evidence.","start":1548.666,"stop":1550.915,"duration":2.25},{"text":"They destroyed the steel inside the house.","start":1550.915,"stop":1553.62,"duration":2.7},{"text":"And --","start":1553.62,"stop":1554.558,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now, Mr. Asinof.","start":1554.558,"stop":1558.48,"duration":3.92}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 08, 1958","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13430","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 331, Roy Jones versus United States of America.","start":0,"stop":9.759,"duration":9.76},{"text":"Had you completed your opening argument, Mr. Asinof?","start":9.759,"stop":12.342,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Chief Justice, I would like to reserve about five minutes of my time (Inaudible)","start":12.342,"stop":16.582,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may reserve the rest of your time if you wish.","start":16.582,"stop":19.295,"duration":2.71},{"text":"Mr. Grimm.","start":19.295,"stop":21.588,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"May it please the Court.","start":21.588,"stop":25.61,"duration":4.02},{"text":"The facts of the case are these.","start":25.61,"stop":27.708,"duration":2.1},{"text":"On April 30, 1956, federal agents in the Northern District of Georgia received a tip from an informant that petitioner had installed a distillery in his farmhouse.","start":27.708,"stop":42.685,"duration":14.98},{"text":"He had -- he had previously had experience along that line and so the agents proceeded to his farmhouse, to the vicinity thereof to investigate the situation.","start":42.685,"stop":54.242,"duration":11.56},{"text":"They found spent mash running from a rubber hose into a small river, in a hollow behind the farmhouse and traces to within approximately 50 yards of the house.","start":54.242,"stop":68.71,"duration":14.47},{"text":"The following day, which is May 1st, 1956, they again returned to the vicinity.","start":68.71,"stop":76.67,"duration":7.96},{"text":"They found at that time, spent mash was once again running into the stream.","start":76.67,"stop":81.728,"duration":5.06},{"text":"They could smell the odor of cooking mash in the area.","start":81.728,"stop":85.419,"duration":3.69},{"text":"They could hear the sound of a blower burner in operation.","start":85.419,"stop":89.649,"duration":4.23},{"text":"Here, I might say that a blower burner is used to transmit fuel oil to the boiler, which generates steam and steam is then in turn used in distillation process.","start":89.649,"stop":101.592,"duration":11.94},{"text":"They also heard voices and bumping noises and continued their surveillance at that time until about 2:00 a.m.on the morning of May 2nd.","start":101.592,"stop":113.268,"duration":11.68},{"text":"So, as of that time, the agents knew that a distillery was in operation within the farmhouse and they knew that several persons were involved, because for -- from time to time they could see people moving around the premises.","start":113.268,"stop":129.166,"duration":15.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you mind -- would you be good enough to tell me if -- if the record discloses or a -- a judicial notice of it.","start":129.166,"stop":138.306,"duration":9.14},{"text":"This was a farmhouse near Dawsonville.","start":138.306,"stop":140.919,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":140.919,"stop":143.003,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"How do we get the -- was there a United States Commissioner at Dawsonville?","start":143.003,"stop":147.033,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Not so far as I know, Your Honor.","start":147.033,"stop":148.169,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, where was the United States Commissioner?","start":148.169,"stop":150.552,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe --","start":150.552,"stop":150.802,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The nearest access to this farmhouse.","start":150.802,"stop":152.566,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe Andersonville, Georgia.","start":152.566,"stop":154.782,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How far is that?","start":154.782,"stop":156.549,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"It was a drive for the federal officers of about 30 to 45 minutes, each way.","start":156.549,"stop":163.274,"duration":6.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They of course had cars, did they, the federal officers?","start":163.274,"stop":165.847,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"They had one car for the five.","start":165.847,"stop":167.402,"duration":1.55},{"text":"They were five in the group.","start":167.402,"stop":168.368,"duration":0.97},{"text":"I -- I'd like to say on page 40 of the record, State Agent Hollingsworth is testifying and he testified, it took 30 to 45 minutes to drive out there.","start":168.368,"stop":178.049,"duration":9.68},{"text":"Later on that day of May 2nd, in the afternoon, the agents procured a daytime search warrant and proceeded in a party of five again to the vicinity of the farmhouse.","start":178.049,"stop":189.909,"duration":11.86},{"text":"They arrived there in about an hour before darkness.","start":189.909,"stop":193.462,"duration":3.55},{"text":"It was a gray overcast the day.","start":193.462,"stop":195.982,"duration":2.52},{"text":"They took up a position in a small grove across the road from petitioner's farmhouse.","start":195.982,"stop":202.447,"duration":6.47},{"text":"And the agent in charge, elect in charge -- elected to continue his investigation rather than serve the warrant at that time.","start":202.447,"stop":211.065,"duration":8.62},{"text":"He testified that he did this for two reasons.","start":211.065,"stop":213.977,"duration":2.91},{"text":"Number one, he wanted to learn whether any other persons were implicated in the operation of this distillery.","start":213.977,"stop":220.453,"duration":6.48},{"text":"He wanted to learn who they were and he also wanted to learn whether there were any vehicles involved.","start":220.453,"stop":227.259,"duration":6.81},{"text":"It began to rain heavily and the rain slackened off then at about 7:00 p.m. or thereabout.","start":227.259,"stop":235.347,"duration":8.09},{"text":"The agents heard voices from the farmhouse.","start":235.347,"stop":239.766,"duration":4.42},{"text":"The voices inquired whether someone would like to bring up the truck at that time and an unidentified person left the premises and went down to the home of petitioner's father, which is about a quarter of a mile down the road.","start":239.766,"stop":252.881,"duration":13.12},{"text":"Thereafter, a truck was driven into the farmyard and driven around behind the farmhouse, out of sight of the agents.","start":252.881,"stop":261.334,"duration":8.45},{"text":"Then, the agents saw people moving around in the house through a window, a lighted window.","start":261.334,"stop":266.932,"duration":5.6},{"text":"They heard heavy bumping noises, as though heavy objects were being moved.","start":266.932,"stop":272.908,"duration":5.98},{"text":"And -- and about 9:00 or 9:15 p.m., the truck motor was started and the truck began to drive around from the corner of the farmhouse.","start":272.908,"stop":283.183,"duration":10.27},{"text":"The agents then began to move across the road and as the truck arrived at the driveway to the farmhouse it became mired.","start":283.183,"stop":290.197,"duration":7.01},{"text":"At that point, the agents overtook the truck and they arrested two persons who are on the truck.","start":290.197,"stop":296.313,"duration":6.12},{"text":"Number one, James McKinney, who's driving the truck and Grady Jones, the brother of petitioner, was on the back.","start":296.313,"stop":303.512,"duration":7.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What time is that?","start":303.512,"stop":304.54,"duration":1.03},{"text":"What time of the day (Inaudible)","start":304.54,"stop":306.436,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"This was about 9:00 or 9:15 p.m., Your Honor.","start":306.436,"stop":310.348,"duration":3.91},{"text":"They also found 413 gallons of nontaxpaid alcohol on the truck.","start":310.348,"stop":315.936,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Tell me Mr. Grimm, tell me you rely on the arrests of the people on the truck as having any bearing on the lawfulness of the entering of the house?","start":315.936,"stop":326.095,"duration":10.16}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"We rely upon it, only insofar that it contributes to the entering that the -- to the inference that the agents entered for the purpose of making an arrest and not for the purpose of searching for contraband, having made the -- as I will say later, having made two arrests, having known that several persons were involved, having known that one of those persons was petitioner, he not having been on the truck but having been vitally interested of course in the removal of the fruits of his operation from the premises.","start":326.095,"stop":355.778,"duration":29.68},{"text":"We think that we have reasonable inference that the agents could believe that he was therefore in the house.","start":355.778,"stop":361.097,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then that -- that it says a matter of evidence, in other words, that it is evidence which shows light upon that purpose in entering the house is really a purpose to make an arrest.","start":361.097,"stop":372.314,"duration":11.22}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the Government's contention, Your Honor.","start":372.314,"stop":374.118,"duration":1.8},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":374.118,"stop":375.246,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"No arrest wasn't in fact made at that time?","start":375.246,"stop":377.941,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":377.941,"stop":378.089,"duration":0.15},{"text":"As a matter of fact, it was not.","start":378.089,"stop":380.442,"duration":2.35},{"text":"After seized -- after making the arrest on the truck and after seizing the alcohol on the truck, the agents then moved to both the front and back door.","start":380.442,"stop":390.855,"duration":10.41},{"text":"And State Agent Hollingsworth, as a matter of fact, was the first one that came to the front porch.","start":390.855,"stop":395.824,"duration":4.97},{"text":"Now, while they were making the arrest at the truck, an unidentified carrier had come down the public road, turned into the driveway through another entrance or turned into the farmyard through another driveway.","start":395.824,"stop":407.428,"duration":11.6},{"text":"And so when Agent Hollingsworth arrived at the front porch, he found petitioner's wife and petitioner's 12-year-old son there present.","start":407.428,"stop":418.383,"duration":10.95},{"text":"Now, the boy was standing inside the doorway and he was holding a shotgun at point arm.","start":418.383,"stop":424.581,"duration":6.2},{"text":"Hollingsworth asked him to hand over the gun, he refused to do so.","start":424.581,"stop":429.819,"duration":5.24},{"text":"Hollingsworth then asked his mother to tell the boy to hand over the shotgun, she refused to do so.","start":429.819,"stop":437.178,"duration":7.36},{"text":"After some conversation then, Hollingsworth edged closer and finally succeeded in jumping through the doorway and seizing the shotgun.","start":437.178,"stop":445.878,"duration":8.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now Mr. Grimm, in that respect, his testimony.","start":445.878,"stop":449.359,"duration":3.48},{"text":"\"I was standing in the door at that time,” I'm looking at page 38, \"Hadn't entered.","start":449.359,"stop":456.813,"duration":7.45},{"text":"So, ever when the kid got close enough so that I could get to the gun.","start":456.813,"stop":460.945,"duration":4.13},{"text":"I got the gun, sir, got the gun from the kid.\"","start":460.945,"stop":464.586,"duration":3.64},{"text":"Now, does that show that he entered?","start":464.586,"stop":467.109,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, but the District Court expressly found in its findings of fact that the first entry was made by Hollingsworth for the purpose of disarming the boy.","start":467.109,"stop":476.259,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's -- that's the only testimony --","start":476.259,"stop":477.527,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"That's --","start":477.527,"stop":477.874,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is it, upon which (Inaudible)","start":477.874,"stop":478.513,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Page --","start":478.513,"stop":478.892,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- finding the arrest.","start":478.892,"stop":485.299,"duration":6.41}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, except that he had repeated his testimony, but that is the only expressed statement that he made.","start":485.299,"stop":498.822,"duration":13.52}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I thought you support any finding that he had -- he entered to get the gun, does he?","start":498.822,"stop":504.419,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that that is the gist of his entire testimony.","start":504.419,"stop":508.379,"duration":3.96}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How can it be when he says, \"I was standing in the door at that time, hadn't enter.","start":508.379,"stop":514.715,"duration":6.34},{"text":"So, ever when the kid got close enough so that I could get to the gun, I got the gun, sir.","start":514.715,"stop":519.067,"duration":4.35},{"text":"I got the gun from the kid.\"","start":519.067,"stop":520.91,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, here, I should point out that earlier in his testimony -- testimony Hollingsworth said.","start":520.91,"stop":526.131,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that?","start":526.131,"stop":527.177,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"On page 37.","start":527.177,"stop":529.151,"duration":1.97},{"text":"\"I went on the porch, Mr. Jones, was at the porch -- on the porch rather and as I run upon the porch, a small boy there grabbed a shotgun and held it up more or less as at port arms and he went to the back.\"","start":529.151,"stop":540.46,"duration":11.31},{"text":"That is from front to back to the house.","start":540.46,"stop":543.542,"duration":3.08},{"text":"\"I hollered to Woody and Jim that he was coming to the back door with a gun, to look out.\"","start":543.542,"stop":548.211,"duration":4.67},{"text":"And after he went to the backdoor, I told Mrs.Jones, \"Make the boy put the gun down.\"","start":548.211,"stop":552.7,"duration":4.49},{"text":"And she says, \"I'm not going to do it.\"","start":552.7,"stop":554.856,"duration":2.16},{"text":"Asked for a search warrant and I told her, \"We didn't need a search warrant,\" and the kid came back toward me, through the house again and I kept telling him, \"Son, don't you shoot me.","start":554.856,"stop":562.631,"duration":7.77},{"text":"Give me that gun,\" and he never would do it.","start":562.631,"stop":565.346,"duration":2.72},{"text":"I was standing in the door at that time.","start":565.346,"stop":567.1,"duration":1.75},{"text":"I haven't entered.","start":567.1,"stop":568.298,"duration":1.2},{"text":"So, ever when the --","start":568.298,"stop":568.987,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And did --","start":568.987,"stop":569.294,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the kid got close enough -- from this, I think that the inference may flow that the first entry into the residence was made by Hollingsworth to secure the shotgun because the boy had been --","start":569.294,"stop":581.619,"duration":12.33}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't see where you're making this inference that he had entered when he said he hadn't entered.","start":581.619,"stop":588.024,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Not at that point, but then, when the boy got close enough, he -- as he said, went for the gun.","start":588.024,"stop":593.863,"duration":5.84},{"text":"I got to the gun.","start":593.863,"stop":595.478,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And entered at this time was (Inaudible)","start":595.478,"stop":597.372,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":597.372,"stop":598.121,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your predicament.","start":598.121,"stop":599.097,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":599.097,"stop":600.085,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's no dispute that after he disarmed him, they prolonged their visit in the house.","start":600.085,"stop":604.087,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Thereafter, Agent Langford, who was in charge of this group and Agent Evans, entered the house.","start":604.087,"stop":611.962,"duration":7.88},{"text":"Now, in the house, they found petitioner's father --","start":611.962,"stop":614.627,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Before you get to that.","start":614.627,"stop":615.668,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and petitioner's brother.","start":615.668,"stop":617.045,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I noticed that one of the other officers, was it Evans?","start":617.045,"stop":621.496,"duration":4.45},{"text":"I guess he was a federal officer, Hollingsworth was the state officer, wasn't he?","start":621.496,"stop":624.446,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":624.446,"stop":625.075,"duration":0.63},{"text":"All the rest were federal officers.","start":625.075,"stop":626.233,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Federal officers?","start":626.233,"stop":626.98,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Four of them.","start":626.98,"stop":627.617,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I noticed that at page 31, Evans says, \"She,\" that's the wife, \"was standing in the front door.\"","start":627.617,"stop":639.43,"duration":11.81}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":639.43,"stop":639.68,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As I came in, in the door, she was standing in the front door with her hands like this, spread from one side to the door way to the other.","start":639.68,"stop":649.792,"duration":10.11},{"text":"And the trial judge, the finding is that Mrs. Roy Jones undertook to block the door way to keep the officers from entering the dwelling house, telling the officers to wait until her husband Roy Jones returned.","start":649.792,"stop":665.001,"duration":15.21},{"text":"Now, did the officers break-in or forced their way in?","start":665.001,"stop":668.971,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"A little further on, on that page, sir, on page R31.","start":668.971,"stop":672.807,"duration":3.84},{"text":"Question \"Did you push or shove Mrs. Jones or do anything like that?\"","start":672.807,"stop":675.787,"duration":2.98},{"text":"Answer \"I did not touch Mrs. Jones as I went in the house.\"","start":675.787,"stop":678.891,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, even if they didn't, is there -- would -- did she admit them?","start":678.891,"stop":683.992,"duration":5.1},{"text":"Was it they --","start":683.992,"stop":684.172,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know.","start":684.172,"stop":684.899,"duration":0.73},{"text":"I'm willing to -- I'm willing to say that the record shows that she protested their entry.","start":684.899,"stop":690.991,"duration":6.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, have -- then -- then she more than -- what you call their entry then was it --","start":690.991,"stop":694.424,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm -- I'm going permission or did they --","start":694.424,"stop":695.2,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":695.2,"stop":696.159,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no.","start":696.159,"stop":696.646,"duration":0.49},{"text":"She -- she did not consent to the entry and even if she had, I suppose we would have -- that could then be very reasonably said, that well, this was called acquiescence.","start":696.646,"stop":706.865,"duration":10.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then, wasn't it -- wasn't it a breaking-in?","start":706.865,"stop":709.627,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it was an entry of a protest.","start":709.627,"stop":713.909,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That wasn't my question.","start":713.909,"stop":714.985,"duration":1.08},{"text":"Wasn't it a breaking-in (Voice Overlap)?","start":714.985,"stop":716.091,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, the reason -- I don't want to use that language \"breaking-in\" is because \"breaking-in\" for the purpose of arrest, that is in testing whether there was a “breaking-in” in the law of arrest is “breaking” has the same meaning and “breaking” has in the law of burglary.","start":716.091,"stop":734.402,"duration":18.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean that perhaps to be a window forced or a door forced opened?","start":734.402,"stop":737.776,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Or a door opened or something of that sort.","start":737.776,"stop":739.93,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And this would not come into the category of break-in?","start":739.93,"stop":742.712,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":742.712,"stop":743.531,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I gather then, is that the reason the Government hasn't taken the position it did in the Miller case a few weeks ago that it would be necessary to give notice of the purpose of coming in if you are breaking-in?","start":743.531,"stop":753.468,"duration":9.94}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, here -- here, sir, first, I must say that on -- on the motion to suppress which was filed by petitioner, he contended that the search was unreasonable and that he had not consented to it and he spelled out no specific reason why he believes to be unreasonable.","start":753.468,"stop":768.088,"duration":14.62},{"text":"Now, at the trial, an issue was never made, as it was in the Miller, as to whether or not the agents had given notice of their purpose before entry.","start":768.088,"stop":776.678,"duration":8.59},{"text":"And so, in the course of a narrative statement, Agent Langford testified that he told Mrs. Millers his name.","start":776.678,"stop":782.048,"duration":5.37},{"text":"He told her that he was a federal officer.","start":782.048,"stop":787.096,"duration":5.05},{"text":"She asked for a search warrant.","start":787.096,"stop":788.491,"duration":1.39},{"text":"He said that he didn't need any and that he intended to enter.","start":788.491,"stop":792.393,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But he never told her why he wanted to go in.","start":792.393,"stop":794.449,"duration":2.06},{"text":"He never told her he was entering for the purpose of arresting the petitioner, did he?","start":794.449,"stop":797.96,"duration":3.51}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the record does not show that he ever told her that and he was never asked.","start":797.96,"stop":802.16,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, he didn't tell anybody the purpose, did he?","start":802.16,"stop":804.932,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":804.932,"stop":804.97,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Why he was entering?","start":804.97,"stop":806.275,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"The record simply doesn't say, Your Honor.","start":806.275,"stop":807.812,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":807.812,"stop":808.481,"duration":0.67},{"text":"Whether we got what the record to go upon, is there anything in the record at all that shows that he announced his purpose for desiring to enter?","start":808.481,"stop":815.315,"duration":6.83}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":815.315,"stop":815.515,"duration":0.2},{"text":"There is nothing in the record that shows that, Your Honor.","start":815.515,"stop":817.439,"duration":1.92},{"text":"On the hand, it was never an issue in this case.","start":817.439,"stop":819.924,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I'm just interested how the Government distinguishes this from the Miller case, the position that took there was that even if it was an entry on probable cause to make an arrest, it would be unlawful entry except there's a purpose to the (Inaudible)","start":819.924,"stop":836.237,"duration":16.31}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, all I -- I don't believe that there's any inconsistency here, Your Honor.","start":836.237,"stop":841.606,"duration":5.37},{"text":"There, in the Miller case, there was an issue as to whether they had announced the purpose for their entry.","start":841.606,"stop":848.031,"duration":6.42},{"text":"Here, it never was an issue.","start":848.031,"stop":850.806,"duration":2.78},{"text":"No one --","start":850.806,"stop":851.315,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if this was breaking-in --","start":851.315,"stop":851.595,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"-- regardless of the relevance of the law, and so the officers (Voice Overlap) --","start":851.595,"stop":853.829,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If this was a breaking-in, as to which a prior statement of purpose for the breaking is required, would it be any less and unlawful entry because the petitioner didn't raise the question?","start":853.829,"stop":869.095,"duration":15.27}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- it would not be any -- the less provided that the record established that.","start":869.095,"stop":875.956,"duration":6.86},{"text":"But here, I will -- I cannot accept the proposition that there was a breaking-in.","start":875.956,"stop":881.044,"duration":5.09}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is because they didn't break a door or a window and that's your --","start":881.044,"stop":885.743,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"If I will --","start":885.743,"stop":886.28,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- view of what's the breaking is?","start":886.28,"stop":888.284,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":888.284,"stop":888.811,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is your view of what a breaking is?","start":888.811,"stop":890.655,"duration":1.84},{"text":"There couldn't be if they did force their way pass Mrs. Jones, that would not be a break-in?","start":890.655,"stop":895.575,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"So long as -- well, so long as there was no manhandling, no touching, no forcing her out of the way, certainly.","start":895.575,"stop":905.588,"duration":10.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what was it if they entered over her protest.","start":905.588,"stop":908.081,"duration":2.49},{"text":"Well, (Voice Overlap) --","start":908.081,"stop":908.321,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, she told him she didn't -- she told them that she wanted them to wait until -- until --","start":908.321,"stop":913.119,"duration":4.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, what kind of entry was it then?","start":913.119,"stop":914.716,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Was -- was --","start":914.716,"stop":915.083,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"What sir?","start":915.083,"stop":916.011,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They weren't admitted voluntarily, wasn't it?","start":916.011,"stop":918.257,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":918.257,"stop":919.413,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then they entered what?","start":919.413,"stop":922.854,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's simply they entered over her protest.","start":922.854,"stop":927.016,"duration":4.16},{"text":"They did not break-in.","start":927.016,"stop":932.044,"duration":5.03},{"text":"Having --","start":932.044,"stop":932.311,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"She was -- suppose she was out on the porch and -- and protested the entry and they just paid no attention to it, went over and opened the door and walked in, would that -- would that be a break-in, an entry?","start":932.311,"stop":946.442,"duration":14.13}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, once it would depend upon the lawfulness of their entry.","start":946.442,"stop":950.669,"duration":4.23},{"text":"Otherwise, as we argued in Miller and as I say here, they're entitled to break-in or enter on over protest only if they have reasonable cause to believe that they can make a valid arrest inside the house, only if they have probable cause for an arrest and only if they have reason to believe that the person that they seek is within the house.","start":950.669,"stop":980.9,"duration":30.23},{"text":"And so, once again, it is not the determinative factor in testing whether the entry is illegal.","start":980.9,"stop":990.341,"duration":9.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the District Court make any finding pf the purpose of the entry was to make an arrest?","start":990.341,"stop":997.835,"duration":7.49}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Here, I must say that the District Court's finding was rather ambiguous.","start":997.835,"stop":1002.645,"duration":4.81},{"text":"However, we believe fairly implicit within his finding is the drawing of the inference that the agents entered to make an arrest on probable cause.","start":1002.645,"stop":1012.08,"duration":9.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I read the District Court's opinion, it seemed to me that their construction of it was rightly or wrongly, that he said that we didn't have to have a search warrant, that it suffice to have reasonable grounds for believing that there was contraband or something on the premises.","start":1012.08,"stop":1032.241,"duration":20.16},{"text":"And that without a search warrant, that was enough to justify the entry.","start":1032.241,"stop":1036.393,"duration":4.15},{"text":"And you don't undertake to defend the case on that basis.","start":1036.393,"stop":1039.084,"duration":2.69},{"text":"Now, that's the way I read the record.","start":1039.084,"stop":1041.028,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Taylor case is on the books.","start":1041.028,"stop":1045.699,"duration":4.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It's -- yes, it is.","start":1045.699,"stop":1047.284,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Johnson is on the books.","start":1047.284,"stop":1051.444,"duration":4.16},{"text":"There are other cases --","start":1051.444,"stop":1052.45,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But isn't it -- isn't it --","start":1052.45,"stop":1052.717,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of similar import --","start":1052.717,"stop":1053.945,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't the -- isn't the -- to be frank about it, isn't the plain truth in the matter that you don't undertake to justify the search on the premise -- on the premises on which the District Court put them?","start":1053.945,"stop":1065.98,"duration":12.04}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1065.98,"stop":1066.277,"duration":0.3},{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I -- we do not defend this on the proposition that a probable cause to make a search for contraband alone justifies an entry.","start":1066.277,"stop":1074.284,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It has to be an incident to an arrest, that's your case?","start":1074.284,"stop":1076.799,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it has to be incident to an arrest or it has to be an entry made for the purpose of making an arrest.","start":1076.799,"stop":1083.493,"duration":6.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1083.493,"stop":1084.192,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"On reasonable cause to believe that appellant is within the house.","start":1084.192,"stop":1088.603,"duration":4.41},{"text":"Now --","start":1088.603,"stop":1089.471,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You left me -- you left me in doubt --","start":1089.471,"stop":1089.798,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":1089.798,"stop":1091.176,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- by your answer to the question by Mr. Justice Brennan and to the Chief Justice, namely, are you saying there was no breaking in the circumstance on the fact of this case or are you saying that this -- they had a lawful right to enter.","start":1091.176,"stop":1108.325,"duration":17.15},{"text":"You did no more, of course, that was necessary to make the arrest.","start":1108.325,"stop":1112.318,"duration":3.99},{"text":"You don't have to bother about whether there was or was not a breaking, which is it?","start":1112.318,"stop":1117.007,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"The latter, Your Honor.","start":1117.007,"stop":1118.123,"duration":1.12},{"text":"However --","start":1118.123,"stop":1118.74,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Then -- then you don't have to enter to a colloquy between you and Justice Brennan of what -- what constitutes a breaking is from your point of view to be irrelevant, is that right?","start":1118.74,"stop":1127.977,"duration":9.24}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"In the ultimate resolution of this case, yes, Your Honor.","start":1127.977,"stop":1132.808,"duration":4.83},{"text":"On the other hand, I don't think that the facts carry --","start":1132.808,"stop":1135.521,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I --","start":1135.521,"stop":1136.198,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"-- this case so far as to say there was a breaking.","start":1136.198,"stop":1138.701,"duration":2.5},{"text":"That's all.","start":1138.701,"stop":1138.799,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if it is irrelevant, then the first thing here then -- then you maybe -- you may have to take that other sense you drew up.","start":1138.799,"stop":1147.021,"duration":8.22},{"text":"But the first thing on which you stand, I gather therefore as an answer to Chief Justice's question, that whatever it may be denominated is before -- to be determined nearly as to whether or not it was a breaking, you don't have to pass on it.","start":1147.021,"stop":1163.555,"duration":16.53},{"text":"You will have to take the position, because you justify that the lawful entry to make a lawful arrest, is that right?","start":1163.555,"stop":1170.243,"duration":6.69}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"That is precisely so, Your Honor.","start":1170.243,"stop":1172.487,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, you've got me confused, Mr. Grimm.","start":1172.487,"stop":1175.619,"duration":3.13},{"text":"I thought you told me before that if there was a breaking, if this was a break-in the circumstances of this case, consistent with the position that the Government took in the Miller case.","start":1175.619,"stop":1188.207,"duration":12.59},{"text":"It could not be a lawful entry, even for the purposes of making an arrest on probable cause unless that it was first announced the purpose of the entry.","start":1188.207,"stop":1198.425,"duration":10.22}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"That was -- that was the case in Miller, Your Honor.","start":1198.425,"stop":1201.078,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what -- what are you saying here?","start":1201.078,"stop":1203.172,"duration":2.09},{"text":"Are you saying here that even if there was a breaking, no statement of purpose was required or that there was no breaking in the facts of this case?","start":1203.172,"stop":1210.627,"duration":7.45}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, for the purpose of this argument, for the purposes of this case, I say that it is irrelevant that they entered over protest.","start":1210.627,"stop":1222.493,"duration":11.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that because this was not a breaking?","start":1222.493,"stop":1226.374,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it is because an issue was never made, as it was in the Miller case, as to whether or not they had given notice to the wife --","start":1226.374,"stop":1234.023,"duration":7.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then, if I understand it, that means that even if this was a break-in in these circumstances, since they never heretofore raised the question of the requirement of prior notice of purpose or entry, that is she was not before, is that it?","start":1234.023,"stop":1249.036,"duration":15.01}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1249.036,"stop":1250.164,"duration":1.13},{"text":"That once again we differ as to whether there was a breaking --","start":1250.164,"stop":1253.844,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What --","start":1253.844,"stop":1254.763,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on the fact.","start":1254.763,"stop":1256.887,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"We can understand that the -- or defending a case or this particular case.","start":1256.887,"stop":1262.344,"duration":5.46},{"text":"Okay, this is my position but even if you -- the Court goes against me and then move on to the next one.","start":1262.344,"stop":1267.85,"duration":5.51},{"text":"But I do submit the importance of the clarity of understanding not to mix the two up and say, because I understood to take the position, one, we don't have to consider breaking in this case in view of the fact of the circumstances of the entry for the purpose of the arrest is lawful.","start":1267.85,"stop":1288.408,"duration":20.56}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1288.408,"stop":1288.608,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You think that?","start":1288.608,"stop":1289.684,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1289.684,"stop":1290.171,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You then move on however and say, if the Court's (Inaudible) goes against me on that, I contend in the alternative that in fact there was no question.","start":1290.171,"stop":1298.503,"duration":8.33}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1298.503,"stop":1298.511,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe this position of yours.","start":1298.511,"stop":1300.904,"duration":2.39},{"text":"I suggest --","start":1300.904,"stop":1301.174,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1301.174,"stop":1301.461,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to be kept apart.","start":1301.461,"stop":1303.887,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1303.887,"stop":1306.021,"duration":2.13},{"text":"If I may -- if I may continue, after entry, the agents found petitioner's father and petitioner's brother inside the house.","start":1306.021,"stop":1315.25,"duration":9.23},{"text":"They did not find petitioner.","start":1315.25,"stop":1317.314,"duration":2.06},{"text":"They also found a distillery in a room on the main floor of the house.","start":1317.314,"stop":1323.39,"duration":6.08},{"text":"Leading up in this room was a stairway to the attic.","start":1323.39,"stop":1326.322,"duration":2.93},{"text":"In the attic, they found barrels.","start":1326.322,"stop":1328.378,"duration":2.06},{"text":"They found 2700 gallons of mash, a mash found in all of the other paraphernalia, usually associated with the operation of a distillery.","start":1328.378,"stop":1337.878,"duration":9.5},{"text":"They came back downstairs, inquired with Mrs. Jones and the boy and then went up on the front porch and waited for petitioner.","start":1337.878,"stop":1346.668,"duration":8.79},{"text":"He returned home at about 10:00 p.m. and admitted ownership of the still and denied that the liquor found on the truck came from his operation.","start":1346.668,"stop":1359.962,"duration":13.29},{"text":"Thereafter, the agents made the seizure of the still and destroyed that portion which they could not remove with them.","start":1359.962,"stop":1369.912,"duration":9.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your claim is that the seizure was made after the arrest?","start":1369.912,"stop":1373.323,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1373.323,"stop":1373.503,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They opted it, what occurred before Jones showed up was --","start":1373.503,"stop":1378.132,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1378.132,"stop":1378.529,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- simply a reconnaissance.","start":1378.529,"stop":1379.817,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Was a -- well, it was a search for Jones.","start":1379.817,"stop":1383.128,"duration":3.31},{"text":"I say though on the basis of the fact that it is Roy Jones who tell this -- in his testimony, what it is that the agents did, in connection with this distillery.","start":1383.128,"stop":1396.471,"duration":13.34},{"text":"On page 14, he says the question, “Now, then, did they seize that or destroyed or take it with them or what?”","start":1396.471,"stop":1404.18,"duration":7.71},{"text":"They took part of it with them and destroyed the rest.","start":1404.18,"stop":1406.835,"duration":2.65},{"text":"Destroyed it right there in the house or take it outside?","start":1406.835,"stop":1409.733,"duration":2.9},{"text":"They destroyed everything in the house rather -- rather than the beer or the mash whichever one you might want to call it.","start":1409.733,"stop":1415.911,"duration":6.18},{"text":"They pumped a good deal of heat out and left the rest.","start":1415.911,"stop":1419.432,"duration":3.52},{"text":"This, I take it to -- from this, I believe you can draw the inference that he was there when they did it and that would have to be after he returned.","start":1419.432,"stop":1428.501,"duration":9.07}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Let -- let me see if I get this now.","start":1428.501,"stop":1430.066,"duration":1.57},{"text":"Is this the position that there was no seizure at all until after Jones got home?","start":1430.066,"stop":1434.894,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1434.894,"stop":1436.491,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what was that they have done before that?","start":1436.491,"stop":1438.888,"duration":2.4}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"They had entered and they have looked through the house for petitioner and they had come upon the contraband in plain view.","start":1438.888,"stop":1445.379,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But they've done nothing with anything until he arrived home?","start":1445.379,"stop":1448.491,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":1448.491,"stop":1449.357,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, are you cogitating the legality of the seizure then upon the fact that all were secured after he came home and was placed under arrest?","start":1449.357,"stop":1459.684,"duration":10.33}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"That would not necessarily be so, Your Honor, because we contend that the contraband having been in plain view after a lawful entry and the agents having come upon it in plain view after a lawful entry.","start":1459.684,"stop":1472.266,"duration":12.58},{"text":"It was subject to immediate forfeiture and seizure by these agents.","start":1472.266,"stop":1476.565,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's the position you take in your brief, isn't it?","start":1476.565,"stop":1478.681,"duration":2.12},{"text":"You don't relate this until Jones' returned home.","start":1478.681,"stop":1480.994,"duration":2.31},{"text":"You relate it to the fact that you had a reasonable cause for entering, thinking he was their when you entered, isn't that it?","start":1480.994,"stop":1487.06,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor.","start":1487.06,"stop":1490.321,"duration":3.26},{"text":"However, that is simply the -- the way the facts happened as -- as I believe they are to be found.","start":1490.321,"stop":1499.685,"duration":9.36},{"text":"We do not contend that the search of a dwelling house is justified on probable cause to believe that contraband will be found within.","start":1499.685,"stop":1510.688,"duration":11},{"text":"However, we do believe that agents may -- if they have probable cause to make an arrest and reason to believe that the person they seek is within the dwelling house that they may enter for the purpose of finding him and arresting him.","start":1510.688,"stop":1526.913,"duration":16.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":1526.913,"stop":1527.243,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"And that having -- then, coming upon contraband in plain view, the contraband is subject to seizure.","start":1527.243,"stop":1536.44,"duration":9.2},{"text":"Here, I might also say that this case stands on the same footing as one where an arrest is made after entry, even though no -- as it turned out, no entry -- no arrest was made thereafter because if the test of whether or not they're entitled to make an entry is reasonable cause to believe that the person is within there then the fact that the arrest isn't -- is not made thereafter, cannot be the determining issue.","start":1536.44,"stop":1565.736,"duration":29.3},{"text":"We could not justify an entry by what is found thereafter on the person if someone who was arrested.","start":1565.736,"stop":1571.772,"duration":6.04},{"text":"We could not justify his arrest by the fact that he might be found committing a felony.","start":1571.772,"stop":1577.527,"duration":5.76},{"text":"The test is still whether there was probable cause to believe that he was committing a felony at the time of entry.","start":1577.527,"stop":1584.052,"duration":6.52},{"text":"And so, the fact that an arrest could not be made ultimately, does not measure the lawfulness of the entry.","start":1584.052,"stop":1594.099,"duration":10.05},{"text":"Nonetheless, we come back to the proposition that if they had reason to believe that the person they sought was within the house and if they had probable cause to make an arrest, then the entry is lawful.","start":1594.099,"stop":1608.581,"duration":14.48}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"If Jones had never come back to the house at all, your position would be that they could have seized the --","start":1608.581,"stop":1618.295,"duration":9.71}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"They could have made the seizure at the time --","start":1618.295,"stop":1619.57,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- (Voice Overlap) in the house.","start":1619.57,"stop":1619.748,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"-- they were first within the house.","start":1619.748,"stop":1621.253,"duration":1.5},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1621.253,"stop":1622.429,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your position?","start":1622.429,"stop":1622.756,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What constituted the seizure?","start":1622.756,"stop":1625.661,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"The taking of the barrel, the boiler, and the burner.","start":1625.661,"stop":1630.569,"duration":4.91}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Not the taking possession of the household and what's in there, and dispossessing those who are living there at the time, although they were not -- practically not confused of violating the law themselves?","start":1630.569,"stop":1647.034,"duration":16.47}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":1647.034,"stop":1648.24,"duration":1.21},{"text":"It is --","start":1648.24,"stop":1648.288,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You can do a -- can you break into a house and go all through the -- the house and search it and find something that is -- is contraband and stay there as officers of the law, in charge of it without having made a seizure?","start":1648.288,"stop":1673.355,"duration":25.07}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, by -- by finding and then taking charge of it.","start":1673.355,"stop":1675.93,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean that there is no seizure until -- until they removed it from the premises?","start":1675.93,"stop":1681.539,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say there that the seizure occurs when they first exercised dominion over the --","start":1681.539,"stop":1686.876,"duration":5.34}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"So when did they first exercise dominion in this case?","start":1686.876,"stop":1690.302,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would -- I would say that when they first came upon it --","start":1690.302,"stop":1695.679,"duration":5.38}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":1695.679,"stop":1695.709,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"-- because certainly thereafter, they would not permit anyone to remove it.","start":1695.709,"stop":1698.952,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1698.952,"stop":1699.259,"duration":0.31},{"text":"But now wasn't that -- would then the seizure take place then rather than when Jones came home?","start":1699.259,"stop":1706.166,"duration":6.91}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, in -- in legal theory that might well be --","start":1706.166,"stop":1709.378,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, aren't we talking about --","start":1709.378,"stop":1709.815,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in practical --","start":1709.815,"stop":1710.753,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Aren't we talking about legal seizure?","start":1710.753,"stop":1712.34,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"In -- in practical -- well, yes, Your Honor.","start":1712.34,"stop":1714.975,"duration":2.63},{"text":"But in practical effect, when they put their hands on it, when they made a physical seizure was after Jones returned.","start":1714.975,"stop":1724.034,"duration":9.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What are you relying on now, the time as before the seizure?","start":1724.034,"stop":1730.01,"duration":5.98},{"text":"I understood you a little while ago to say that you dated the seizure from the time that Jones came home, but I understood your question to me that in point of law the seizure actually took place when they took dominion over the home.","start":1730.01,"stop":1747.435,"duration":17.42}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that that is in legal theory when the seizure took place.","start":1747.435,"stop":1751.385,"duration":3.95},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1751.385,"stop":1751.954,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then, for the purposes of this case, when did the seizure take place?","start":1751.954,"stop":1756.653,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"When they came upon the contraband --","start":1756.653,"stop":1759.396,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In --","start":1759.396,"stop":1759.614,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I would say.","start":1759.614,"stop":1759.981,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In the home?","start":1759.981,"stop":1760.54,"duration":0.56},{"text":"Yes.","start":1760.54,"stop":1760.67,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"In the home.","start":1760.67,"stop":1761.037,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1761.037,"stop":1761.556,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Grimm, your time is nearly up and you haven't (Inaudible)","start":1761.556,"stop":1764.141,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":1764.141,"stop":1765.438,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- for me is the most important question.","start":1765.438,"stop":1767.345,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1767.345,"stop":1768.75,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And I'd like to point it.","start":1768.75,"stop":1772.583,"duration":3.83},{"text":"Is it the comment or in relation to a phrase that you've just used a minute that you mentioned before, having gone in there, having entered, was viewed to arresting somebody who they have the right to arrest with probable cause.","start":1772.583,"stop":1788.009,"duration":15.43},{"text":"You used the word, the phrase, “They came upon the things that they seized,” is that right?","start":1788.009,"stop":1793.327,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1793.327,"stop":1794.602,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, did they come upon them then in the sense which come upon means something that they had to find unexpected, a revelation or --","start":1794.602,"stop":1806.241,"duration":11.64}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1806.241,"stop":1806.329,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it's not a fact that for two days, they had probable cause on the basis of which to comply with the Fourth Amendment?","start":1806.329,"stop":1816.556,"duration":10.23}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor --","start":1816.556,"stop":1817.542,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right, that they did had probable cause for two days to go to a Commissioner and get a search warrant, is that right?","start":1817.542,"stop":1825.665,"duration":8.12}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"As of the morning -- 2:00 a.m. in the morning of May 2nd --","start":1825.665,"stop":1829.745,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So from --","start":1829.745,"stop":1830.292,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"-- they had probable cause, at least then.","start":1830.292,"stop":1831.887,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that -- and -- and when did they begin this?","start":1831.887,"stop":1834.829,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that --","start":1834.829,"stop":1835.119,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you give me the order?","start":1835.119,"stop":1835.466,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"That evening, that evening.","start":1835.466,"stop":1837.363,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So they had the whole night, whatever that was, (Voice Overlap).","start":1837.363,"stop":1839.288,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, a day -- a day.","start":1839.288,"stop":1840.744,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"A day.","start":1840.744,"stop":1841.94,"duration":1.2},{"text":"So that for a full day, they could have brought them -- held within the Fourth Amendment, namely, the right of the people to be securing their person, how could a state in effect, against unreasonable search and seizure?","start":1841.94,"stop":1859.04,"duration":17.1},{"text":"The Government interfered with cases and I'm sorry to say that the Court I think has taken that brief out of context against unreasonable search and seizure shall not be violated as no warrant shall issue.","start":1859.04,"stop":1873.154,"duration":14.11},{"text":"In other words, warrant appears there for the first time in relation to what we preceded, namely, an unreasonable search and seizure, is something by which no warrant was issued because it says there, no warrant shall issue.","start":1873.154,"stop":1890.752,"duration":17.6},{"text":"That's the way to avoid unreasonable search and seizure, except in the restricted and limited, and closely confined situation of necessity where you couldn't get a warrant issued.","start":1890.752,"stop":1901.775,"duration":11.02}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor.","start":1901.775,"stop":1902.384,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And you said they came upon it?","start":1902.384,"stop":1904.628,"duration":2.24},{"text":"I point it to you that they had (Inaudible) a day, a whole day which they could have gone to the very (Inaudible) and got to this farm.","start":1904.628,"stop":1914.803,"duration":10.18}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so.","start":1914.803,"stop":1915.581,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So, I think it came upon as a rather -- may I say loosely of describing their experience.","start":1915.581,"stop":1924.604,"duration":9.02}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"But may I -- may I --","start":1924.604,"stop":1926.139,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"As a matter of fact, you were -- you were in the Commissioner's office that day on this same subject and you did do the affidavits where -- that you have probable cause at that time, is it not?","start":1926.139,"stop":1939.152,"duration":13.01}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1939.152,"stop":1940.05,"duration":0.9},{"text":"They -- they had -- as I say, that was after 2:00 a.m. on the morning of May 2nd.","start":1940.05,"stop":1945.64,"duration":5.59},{"text":"That afternoon, they did go and obtained a daytime search warrant.","start":1945.64,"stop":1948.465,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1948.465,"stop":1948.762,"duration":0.3},{"text":"And that was based on probable cause to believe that there was a still in that house.","start":1948.762,"stop":1953.253,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":1953.253,"stop":1953.792,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And that was based on the affidavit of the officers.","start":1953.792,"stop":1956.131,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1956.131,"stop":1957.419,"duration":1.29},{"text":"Now, may -- may I answer your -- take time to answer your question, sir.","start":1957.419,"stop":1959.463,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1959.463,"stop":1960.02,"duration":0.56},{"text":"Go ahead.","start":1960.02,"stop":1961.116,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"First of all, when I used the word “came upon,” they -- they entered the house as we contend to arrest petitioner.","start":1961.116,"stop":1968.689,"duration":7.57},{"text":"Now, there has been a good deal of commotion outside and they could reasonably infer that he might be hiding inside the house.","start":1968.689,"stop":1976.581,"duration":7.89},{"text":"And so, they could look into each room in the house.","start":1976.581,"stop":1980.159,"duration":3.58},{"text":"Now, they didn't know where in the house was the distillery was and when I say, “They came upon it,” I mean, “they came upon,” it's exactly the case (Voice Overlap) --","start":1980.159,"stop":1988.546,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In that case, that was all the issue.","start":1988.546,"stop":1990.181,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1990.181,"stop":1990.987,"duration":0.81},{"text":"Now, insofar as the Fourth Amendment is concerned, it is true as -- as you -- certainly true as you've just said that it begins a person -- people shall be secured against unreasonable searches and seizures and that no warrant shall issue.","start":1990.987,"stop":2007.777,"duration":16.79},{"text":"However, I do not believe that the Amendment has been read by this Court, to mean that the latter portion of the Amendment limits the first portion.","start":2007.777,"stop":2016.991,"duration":9.21},{"text":"And so, through judicial decision, we have evolved the concepts of certain kinds of searches that are reasonable, thus, the search on proper warrant.","start":2016.991,"stop":2026.351,"duration":9.36},{"text":"Search warrant is reasonable, thus, the search incident to arrest is reasonable.","start":2026.351,"stop":2032.03,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Arrest on warrant.","start":2032.03,"stop":2033.994,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":2033.994,"stop":2034.423,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Arrest on warrant.","start":2034.423,"stop":2035.571,"duration":1.15},{"text":"Did this Court ever gone beyond that?","start":2035.571,"stop":2037.325,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Arrest on probable cause.","start":2037.325,"stop":2038.713,"duration":1.39},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, in Agnello.","start":2038.713,"stop":2039.499,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Assert --","start":2039.499,"stop":2040.797,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"In Agnello versus U.S., 269 U.S.10 --","start":2040.797,"stop":2044.627,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Wasn't that the one where they saw him through the window?","start":2044.627,"stop":2047.112,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2047.112,"stop":2047.761,"duration":0.65},{"text":"But that was an arrest on --","start":2047.761,"stop":2048.37,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's very different from this one, is it not?","start":2048.37,"stop":2050.264,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"That was an arrest on probable cause, Your Honor.","start":2050.264,"stop":2052.918,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Without warrant?","start":2052.918,"stop":2053.565,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Without warrant.","start":2053.565,"stop":2054.502,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"As to what?","start":2054.502,"stop":2055.181,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Where they saw the actual crime through the window being committed?","start":2055.181,"stop":2058.393,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"It was committed --","start":2058.393,"stop":2059.639,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2059.639,"stop":2060.465,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the construction is, it's committed in their presence because they saw it, but a felony is also generally construed to be in your presence --","start":2060.465,"stop":2068.221,"duration":7.76}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suggest you do.","start":2068.221,"stop":2069.087,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":2069.087,"stop":2069.266,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a very different case than the one we have here.","start":2069.266,"stop":2073.815,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May I say that I'm entirely -- I think your answer to my question is that -- actually, I won't say it fairly because I assumed counsel -- I assumed the counsel (Inaudible) in answering the question.","start":2073.815,"stop":2084.824,"duration":11.01},{"text":"I think it's accurate and that's why I question your -- your petition here, it's the argument yesterday in asking him whether he's asking us to overrule or whether he is standing on the cases that has been decided because I think you're quite right in making the comment that was made.","start":2084.824,"stop":2105.692,"duration":20.87},{"text":"But I wish to add to that that in the field which -- in which there has been so much conflict, such conflict within the Court.","start":2105.692,"stop":2114.96,"duration":9.27},{"text":"I respect the decision as long as it stands.","start":2114.96,"stop":2118.324,"duration":3.36},{"text":"We're dealing here with a constitutional problem as to which it has been continuous difficulty and difference in the Court.","start":2118.324,"stop":2125.528,"duration":7.2},{"text":"And therefore, I suggest that the Government ought to be prepared to defend their position and not here withstand on the immediate result of a contested case.","start":2125.528,"stop":2138.228,"duration":12.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":2138.228,"stop":2142.925,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":2142.925,"stop":2143.701,"duration":0.78},{"text":"Kindly --","start":2143.701,"stop":2144.63,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) provided by law.","start":2144.63,"stop":2146.624,"duration":1.99},{"text":"It took a long copy of Rabinowitz with them, when they made this search.","start":2146.624,"stop":2150.526,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"[Laugh]","start":2150.526,"stop":2152.253,"duration":1.73},{"text":"I don't believe I said that, Your Honor.","start":2152.253,"stop":2155.764,"duration":3.51},{"text":"Whether or not they did.","start":2155.764,"stop":2156.271,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Could we reject that they were entitled to stand on it, if it's covered?","start":2156.271,"stop":2160.151,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Engene L. Grimm","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes -- yes, sir, surely.","start":2160.151,"stop":2162.217,"duration":2.07},{"text":"And it is one of the later pronouncements of this Court.","start":2162.217,"stop":2166.938,"duration":4.72},{"text":"Thank you Your Honors.","start":2166.938,"stop":2169.737,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Asinof, you may close your argument.","start":2169.737,"stop":2175.099,"duration":5.36}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"I would like to take the remaining time that I have to answer a question from Mr. Justice Brennan, with reference to the force angle that was used in -- and call the Court's attention to the brief filed by the petitioner on page 19 of that brief.","start":2175.099,"stop":2195.774,"duration":20.67},{"text":"There's an appendix in there of the testimony of Mrs.Roy Jones as to this particular portion, right toward the bottom of the page, this is her answer.","start":2195.774,"stop":2206.1,"duration":10.33},{"text":"Speaking about the agent, the federal agent, he says, “We don't wait.”","start":2206.1,"stop":2211.917,"duration":5.82},{"text":"So, he kept pushing and I kept pushing back and they'd sling me first one way and the other.","start":2211.917,"stop":2216.758,"duration":4.84},{"text":"But then, I come back on them and there's one of them, that little old, I don't know which one he was, a little short one, he told my little boy, he said, “You stand back or I slap your brains out,” and I say, “You won't put your hands on my kid.”","start":2216.758,"stop":2230.178,"duration":13.42},{"text":"And I asked the question, “How old is that little boy?”","start":2230.178,"stop":2233.322,"duration":3.14},{"text":"And said -- she said, “Well, he was 12 at that time.”","start":2233.322,"stop":2236.284,"duration":2.96},{"text":"I say, “You won't put your hands on my kid.”","start":2236.284,"stop":2238.44,"duration":2.16},{"text":"He says, “I'll slap his damn brains out,” and there was another one there.","start":2238.44,"stop":2241.652,"duration":3.21},{"text":"He said to that other one, he says, “Here, put this handcuffs on him.”","start":2241.652,"stop":2244.674,"duration":3.02},{"text":"He slapped my hands behind me and got one of the handcuffs on me.","start":2244.674,"stop":2248.175,"duration":3.5},{"text":"Woody come up and say, “You take the handcuffs off of her,” so he took the handcuffs off of me.","start":2248.175,"stop":2252.894,"duration":4.72},{"text":"And then right on the bottom of page 20, in response to a question on cross-examination by the District Attorney.","start":2252.894,"stop":2260.726,"duration":7.83},{"text":"Question “And they didn't do anything to you except to go pass you and get into the house?”","start":2260.726,"stop":2264.416,"duration":3.69},{"text":"Answer “No.","start":2264.416,"stop":2265.185,"duration":0.77},{"text":"They -- I was at the door and they pushed me against the side of the door and I run in front of them again.","start":2265.185,"stop":2269.125,"duration":3.94},{"text":"They would push me back up against the wall and I'd come back and I'd pushed them again.","start":2269.125,"stop":2274.145,"duration":5.02},{"text":"And when they put their feet and skinned -- well, they had skinned my feet all over kicking.","start":2274.145,"stop":2277.345,"duration":3.2},{"text":"I reckon not stopping, as I was pushing them backwards.”","start":2277.345,"stop":2280.616,"duration":3.27},{"text":"Now, the record just shows that this was --","start":2280.616,"stop":2283.261,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Where do you recall that, in your appendix in your brief?","start":2283.261,"stop":2285.455,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2285.455,"stop":2285.952,"duration":0.5},{"text":"It's in the appendix on page 19 and 20.","start":2285.952,"stop":2287.738,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You have it printed in the record?","start":2287.738,"stop":2289.176,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":2289.176,"stop":2289.663,"duration":0.49},{"text":"We -- we omitted it from printing, but we put in the other -- in as much as the Solicitor General put this of it.","start":2289.663,"stop":2295.082,"duration":5.42},{"text":"Now, I'd like to call the Court's attention also to another question as for Mr. Justice Brennan yesterday.","start":2295.082,"stop":2301.349,"duration":6.27},{"text":"On page 51 of the record, this testimony appears in here a question.","start":2301.349,"stop":2307.335,"duration":5.99},{"text":"“What was the reason, please sir, that you told Mrs.Jones that you did not need a search warrant or didn't have one?”","start":2307.335,"stop":2312.264,"duration":4.93},{"text":"Answer “Because I thought we had sufficient evidence to go in the premises without a search warrant.”","start":2312.264,"stop":2316.556,"duration":4.29},{"text":"Question “You didn't exhibit this search warrant that you had to her?”","start":2316.556,"stop":2319.708,"duration":3.15},{"text":"Answer “I did not.","start":2319.708,"stop":2320.644,"duration":0.94},{"text":"That was a daytime search warrant.”","start":2320.644,"stop":2322.93,"duration":2.29},{"text":"And on page 54 of the record, the trial judge found this as a matter of fact, as to the entry.","start":2322.93,"stop":2328.337,"duration":5.41},{"text":"Mrs. Jones asked Officer Woody Langford if he had a search warrant and Langford replied that he did not need one and the officers then searched the premises without a search warrant, with reference to question asked by Mr. Justice Frankfurter.","start":2328.337,"stop":2343.262,"duration":14.93},{"text":"On the same page, the trial judge found this as a matter of fact with reference to the -- he says the house had only two or three doors and they were five officers watching the residence and would have been possible for the officers to watch each of the doors and still send another officer for a nighttime search warrant had the officers deemed this to be necessary.","start":2343.262,"stop":2360.879,"duration":17.62},{"text":"At the bottom of the page, in the trial judge's findings of fact, he says, \"The Court finds that probable cause for the search existed at the time the search was made.","start":2360.879,"stop":2369.085,"duration":8.21},{"text":"There was no finding that there was any question of going in there for the purpose of making an arrest,\" as contended by the Government in this Court.","start":2369.085,"stop":2376.309,"duration":7.22},{"text":"Now, this, if the Court please, we say that this case is on all fours with the Kaplan case.","start":2376.309,"stop":2383.465,"duration":7.16},{"text":"It was decided by Judge Learned Hand in the Second Circuit Court of Appeals, I believe.","start":2383.465,"stop":2388.387,"duration":4.92},{"text":"On page -- page 5 of our reply brief.","start":2388.387,"stop":2393.674,"duration":5.29},{"text":"In that case, the Second Circuit Court of Appeals with reference to a warrant of arrest and this case was -- certiorari was denied by this Court.","start":2393.674,"stop":2402.286,"duration":8.61},{"text":"The Court said this, “The statute certainly requires a warrant when there is time to obtain one that this concession is limited to occasions when it is not safe to wait,” and they were speaking of arrest warrants in that case.","start":2402.286,"stop":2413.842,"duration":11.56},{"text":"Now, we respectfully submit that in this case, the record shows that there was no question, but what they did have was an ample amount of time to have obtained some warrant of some kind, either to search or to arrest.","start":2413.842,"stop":2425.871,"duration":12.03}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there a warrant of arrest in Rabinowitz, if you got them?","start":2425.871,"stop":2429.332,"duration":3.46}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"There was a warrant for arrest in Rabinowitz and it was based upon that warrant.","start":2429.332,"stop":2433.444,"duration":4.11},{"text":"Now, we respect --","start":2433.444,"stop":2434.253,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it mean the implication of what we've just said, if isn't it, that although they could have searched and seized more particularly to the extent that it was done in this case as an incident, in the Government's point of view, before there was an arrest, assume that.","start":2434.253,"stop":2458.064,"duration":23.81}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2458.064,"stop":2461.136,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That opportunity or that right is denied or simply, it doesn't come into play, is there a matter of fact, before the necessity for making the arrest, they could have got a search warrant to search and seize what they did into that search?","start":2461.136,"stop":2481.177,"duration":20.04}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":2481.177,"stop":2481.536,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that what you're saying?","start":2481.536,"stop":2482.375,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Wesley R. Asinof","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":2482.375,"stop":2485.828,"duration":3.45}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Apr  7 - 8, 1958","petitioner":"Jones","respondent":"United States","docket":"331","citation":"357 US 493 (1958)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/357/493","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 30, 1958"}